[38.958807, "o", "cat finding.txt\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[38.95965, "o", "FINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocked by Overly Restrictive String Matching Rules\r\n\r\nAFFECTED RULES:\r\n- Line 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Line 8: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Line 9: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n- Line 10: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n\r\nROOT CAUSE:\r\nThe iptables ruleset implements user-agent filtering by searching for the string \"Mozilla\" in HTTP/HTTPS traffic before accepting connections. If this string is not found in the packet payload, the traffic falls through to the subsequent DROP rules (lines 9-10).\r\n\r\nWHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP DOESN'T:\r\n- SSH (port 22): Has an unconditional ACCEPT rule with no string matching requirements (line 6)\r\n- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80, 443): Require the string \"Mozilla\" to be present in the packet payload\r\n- Tools like curl send \"curl/X.X.X\" as their User-Agent, which doesn't contain \"Mozilla\"\r\n- Browsers typically send User-Agent headers containing \"M"]
[38.959701, "o", "ozilla/5.0\", so they would work\r\n\r\nIMPACT:\r\nThis configuration blocks legitimate HTTP clients including:\r\n- Command-line tools (curl, wget, etc.)\r\n- API clients and scripts\r\n- Monitoring systems\r\n- Any non-browser HTTP client\r\n\r\nRECOMMENDATION:\r\nThe string matching approach for user-agent filtering at the iptables level is problematic because:\r\n1. It inspects packet payloads, which is inefficient and unreliable\r\n2. It blocks legitimate automated tools and monitoring\r\n3. User-Agent strings are easily spoofed, providing minimal security benefit\r\n4. It breaks standard HTTP client functionality\r\n\r\nThe organization should either:\r\n- Remove the string matching rules entirely and implement user-agent filtering at the application layer (web server) where it can be done more intelligently\r\n- Remove the DROP rules and allow all HTTP/HTTPS traffic, relying on application-level controls\r\n- If bot filtering is the goal, use proper rate limiting or implement a WAF solution\r\n"]
[38.959802, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[38.95983, "o", "user@cd4633f8d76b:~/pentest$ "]
